The Farmer's Tale
On that very day, Jesus went out from the house and sat by the Sea of Galilee.
Large crowds gathered around him. He got into a boat. He sat in it. All the people on the shore stood up.
Then he told them many things through stories, saying, "A farmer went out to sow his seed.
He scattered the seeds on the ground. Some fell on the path. Birds came and ate them.
Some seeds fell on rocky places, where there was little soil. The plants grew quickly, because the soil was not deep.
When the sun rose, it scorched the plants. They withered because they had no roots.
Some seeds fell among the thorns. The thorns grew and the plants were choked.
And other seeds fell on good soil. They produced a hundred, sixty, or thirty times what was sown.
"Whoever has ears, let them hear."
The disciples came to him. They asked, "Why do you use stories when you talk to people?"
He answered, "It has been given to you to know the mysteries of the kingdom of heaven, but to them it has not been given.
Everyone who has that kind of knowledge will be given more. In fact, he will have abundance. But he who does not have that kind of knowledge, even the little he has will be taken from him.
Here's the reason I use stories when I talk to people. I say, "They look, but they don't really see. They listen, but they don't really hear or understand."
In them is fulfilled the prophecy of Isaiah: "You will indeed hear, but you will not understand. You will surely see, but you will not perceive."
"Their hearts are calloused. They barely hear with their ears. They have closed their eyes, lest they see with their eyes, lest they hear with their ears, lest they understand with their hearts, lest they turn to the Lord and He heal them." (Isaiah 6:9, 10)
But blessed are your eyes, for they see. And blessed are your ears, for they hear.
What I am going to tell you is the truth. Many prophets and righteous people wanted to see what you see. But they didn't see it. They wanted to hear what you hear. But they didn't hear it.
Listen! This is the meaning of the farmer's story.
People hear the message about the kingdom but do not understand it. Then the evil one comes. He steals what was sown in their hearts. These people are like the seed sown on the path.
But those who received the seed on rocky ground are the ones who hear the word and immediately receive it with joy.
But they have no roots. Therefore they do not last long. They quickly fall away from the faith when difficulties or suffering come because of the message.
As for the seeds that fell among the thorns, these are the ones who hear the word, but the cares of this life and the deceitfulness of wealth choke it, making it unfruitful.
But others received the seed that fell on good soil. These are the ones who hear the message and understand it. They produce a crop, yielding a hundred, sixty or thirty times what was sown. - The Parable of the Weeds
Jesus told the crowd another parable. "The kingdom of heaven," he said, "is like a man who sowed good seed in his field.
But while everyone was sleeping, his enemy came. The enemy planted weeds among the wheat and then left.
The wheat began to grow and form grains. At the same time, weeds appeared.
The owner's servants came to him. They said, "Sir, didn't you sow good seed in your field? Then where did the weeds come from?"
He said, "An enemy did this." The servants asked him, "Do you want us to go and weed it out?"
"No," the owner replied. "While you're pulling the weeds, you might pull up the wheat with them."
Let both grow together until the harvest. Then I will tell the reapers to gather the weeds first and tie them in bundles to be burned, then gather the wheat and bring it into my barn." Parables of the Mustard Seed and Yeast
