Then Jesus answered and said to her, "O woman, great is your faith! Let it be to you as you desire." And her daughter was healed from that very hour. Jesus Feeds the Four Thousand
Jesus left that place. He walked along the Sea of Galilee. Then he went up on a mountainside and sat down.
A large crowd gathered around him. They brought to him the blind and those who could not walk. They also brought the crippled, those who could not speak, and many others. They placed them at his feet, and he healed them.
The people were amazed. Those who could not speak began to speak. Those who were paralyzed were healed. Those who could not walk began to walk. Those who were blind could see. So the people praised the God of Israel.
Then Jesus called his disciples to him and said, "I have great compassion on this crowd. They have been with me for three days now and have nothing to eat. I do not want to send them away hungry, or they may collapse on the way home."
His disciples answered him, "There is nothing here but five loaves and two fish." "How far shall we go and buy enough bread to feed this great multitude?" they asked.
Jesus asked, "How many loaves do you have?" They answered, "Seven, and a few small fish."
Jesus told the crowd to sit on the ground.
He took the seven loaves and the fish, and having given thanks, he broke them and gave them to the disciples. And the disciples gave them to the people.
They all ate and were satisfied. The disciples then gathered seven baskets of the remaining fragments.
The number of men who ate was 4000. The women and children also ate.
After Jesus had sent the crowds away, he got into the boat and went to the region of Magadan.
Jesus is asked for a sign as a miracle.
The Pharisees and Sadducees came to test Jesus. They asked him to show them a sign, a miracle from heaven.
He replied, "In the evening you look at the sky. You say, 'The weather will be good. The sky is red.'"
In the morning you say, "Today will be stormy. The sky is red and cloudy." You know the meaning of what you see in the sky. But you cannot understand the signs of what is happening now.
"An evil and adulterous generation seeks for a sign, but no sign will be given to it except the sign of Jonah." And he left them and went away. The leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees
The pupils crossed to the other side of the lake. They forgot to bring bread.
Jesus said to them, "Beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees."
The pupils talked about it among themselves. They said, "He must be saying this because we didn't bring any bread."
Jesus knew what they were saying. He said to them, "Your faith is so small! Why are you talking among yourselves about having no bread?"
Don't you understand yet? Don't you remember the five loaves for the five thousand? Don't you remember how many baskets of pieces were gathered?
Do you not remember the seven loaves of the four thousand? Do you not remember how many baskets of pieces you gathered?
How can you not understand? I was not talking to you about bread. Beware of the yeast of the Pharisees and Sadducees.
Then the disciples understood that Jesus was not telling them to beware of the leaven of bread, but of the doctrine of the Pharisees and Sadducees. Peter said that Jesus is the Christ.
Jesus went to the region of Caesarea Philippi. There he asked his disciples, "Who do people say the Son of Man is?"
They answered, "Some say John the Baptist; others say Elijah; and others, Jeremiah or one of the prophets."
"But what about you?" he asked. "Who do you say that I am?"
Simon Peter answered, "You are the Christ, the Son of the living God."
Jesus answered, "Blessed are you, Simon son of Jonah! For flesh and blood has not revealed this to you, but my Father who is in heaven.
This is what I tell you. You are Peter. On this rock I will build my church. The gates of hell will not be strong enough to destroy it.
I will give you the keys of the kingdom of heaven. Whatever you bind on earth will be bound in heaven, and whatever you loose on earth will be loosed in heaven.
Then Jesus warned his disciples not to tell anyone that he was the Messiah. Jesus speaks of his upcoming death.
From that time Jesus began to show his disciples that he must go to Jerusalem, and suffer many things from the elders and chief priests and scribes, and be killed, and on the third day be raised.
Peter took Jesus aside and began to rebuke him. He said, "Impossible, Lord! This will never happen to you!"
Jesus turned and said to Peter, "Get behind me, Satan! You are a stumbling block to me; for you are not setting your mind on the things of God, but on the things of man."
Then Jesus spoke to his disciples. He said, "If anyone wants to follow me, he must deny himself. He must take up his cross and follow me.
If he wants to save his life, he will lose it. But if he loses his life for my sake, he will find it.
What good is it for someone to gain the whole world, yet forfeit their soul? Or what can anyone give in exchange for their soul?
The Son of Man will come in his Father's glory, and his angels with him. And then he will reward each one according to what they have done.
What I am about to tell you is true. Some who are standing here will not taste death before they see the Son of Man coming in his kingdom.
The appearance of Jesus changed.
After six days Jesus took with him Peter, James, and John his brother, and led them up to a high mountain by themselves.
There before them, his appearance was transformed. His face shone like the sun. His clothes became white as light.
At that moment, Moses and Elijah appeared before them. Moses and Elijah were speaking with Jesus.
Peter said to Jesus, "Lord, it is good that we are here. If you wish, I will make three shelters: one for you, one for Moses, and one for Elijah."
While Peter was still speaking, a bright cloud enveloped them. A voice from the cloud said, "This is my Son, whom I love. I am very pleased with him. Listen to him!"
When the pupils heard this, they were terrified. They fell on their faces to the ground.
But Jesus came and touched them. He said, "Arise, do not be afraid."
When they looked up, they saw no one but Jesus.
They came down from the mountain. On the way down, Jesus told them what to do. He said, "Don't tell anyone what you saw. Wait until the Son of Man has risen from the dead."
The disciples asked him, "Why do the scribes say that Elijah must come first?"
Jesus answered, "That is true. Elijah is supposed to come and make all things new again.
But I say to you, Elijah has already come, and they did not recognize him, but did to him whatever they pleased. So also will the Son of Man suffer at their hands.
Then the disciples understood that Jesus was speaking to them about John the Baptist. Jesus healed a boy who had a demon.
As they approached the crowd, a man came up to Jesus. He knelt down before him on his knees.
He said, "Oh Lord, have mercy on my son. He shivers greatly and suffers much. Often he falls into the fire or into the water.
I brought him to your disciples, but they could not heal him.
Jesus said, "You hypocritical and evil people! How much longer must I be with you? How much longer must I bear with you? Bring the boy to me."
Jesus commanded the demon to come out of the boy, and it did. He was healed instantly.
Then the disciples came to Jesus in private and asked, "Why couldn't we cast out the demon?"
He replied, "Because your faith is so small. What I'm about to tell you is true. If you have faith as small as a mustard seed, you can say to this mountain, 'Move from here to there,' and it will move. Nothing will be impossible for you."
